Description.note: Lawrence Pohl was writer for movies and theater. He is credited as a contract writer for the movie Breakfast for Two (1937), a story writer for The Big Shot (1937) and Lets Make a Million (1936) (AFI catalog). He co-wrote three plays which were produced from 1934 to 1941: "Preface to Love" with Thomas Ahearn, "Alley Cat" with Alan Dinehart, and "Wise Girl" with Betty Laidlaw. He also co-wrote two screenplays with Thomas Ahearn that were not produced: "Let's be Candid," and "Take the Heir," the latter purchased by R.-K.-O.|~|Negative misfiled in enclosure with Dore Schary

Description.note: Nina Wilcox Putnam was an author who occasionally wrote for the movies. Project Name: Columbia Pictures Stills and Key books
Type.genre: Black-and-white photographs|~|film stills|~|Portrait photographs|~|cellulose nitrate film
Author: Pohle, Lawrence
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Department of Special Collections
Description.note: Lawrence Pohl was writer for movies and theater. He is credited as a contract writer for the movie Breakfast for Two (1937), a story writer for The Big Shot (1937) and Lets Make a Million (1936) (AFI catalog). He co-wrote three plays which were produced from 1934 to 1941: "Preface to Love" with Thomas Ahearn, "Alley Cat" with Alan Dinehart, and "Wise Girl" with Betty Laidlaw. He also co-wrote two screenplays with Thomas Ahearn that were not produced: "Let's be Candid," and "Take the Heir," the latter purchased by R.-K.-O.
Title: Lawrence Pohle (probably), writer, circa 1936-1937
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.
Relation.isPartOf: Columbia Pictures Stills and Key books. Department of Special Collections, Charles E. Young Research Library, UCLA.
Summary: Text from negative enclosure: Lawrence Poble [sic, probably "Pohle"]

Description.note: Director Lewis Milestone and screenwriter Laurence Stallings did not collaborate on any Columbia Pictures films that were produced. However, according to the Los Angeles Times article, "True View of Russia to be Given in Film: Milestone, Stallings Back from Moscow Trip with Unique View," [10 Dec. 1933: B1], the two men were planning a film called "Red Square" to be produced by Columbia. The film was never made.
Title: Lewis Milestone, director, looking over the shoulder of Laurence Stallings, screenwriter, circa 1933
